---
import AiPage from '../layouts/AiPage.astro';
---
<AiPage
  title="What are MCP servers? The ones worth knowing | KB Cafe"
  description="MCP servers are what you actually plug into an AI: files, databases, GitHub, the live web, browsers. A practical tour of the categories and real servers (filesystem, postgres, github, playwright, brave-search), how to read the list, and how to connect one. With a hands-on match-the-server exercise."
  path="/what-are-mcp-servers"
  eyebrow="AI Explained · Protocol"
  h1="What are MCP servers?"
  tagline="If MCP is the standard plug, a server is the appliance you plug in. Here are the kinds worth knowing, with real examples and a hands-on exercise."
>
  <h2>The protocol versus the servers</h2>
  <p>
    <a class="kb-term" href="/dictionary/mcp">MCP</a> is the standard; an MCP <strong>server</strong> is a thing you
    connect through it. The protocol defines how an AI app and a server talk; each server exposes one specific
    capability, your files, a database, a GitHub repo, the live web, and offers it to the model. You learn the protocol
    once in <a href="/what-is-mcp">What is MCP</a>. This lesson is about the servers you actually plug in, because that is
    where MCP stops being abstract.
  </p>

  <h2>What a server hands the model</h2>
  <p>
    A server gives the model a small set of named tools, and sometimes data resources, that it can call through
    <a class="kb-term" href="/dictionary/tool-calling">tool calling</a>. A filesystem server offers tools like &ldquo;read
    file,&rdquo; &ldquo;write file,&rdquo; and &ldquo;list directory.&rdquo; A Postgres server offers &ldquo;run
    query.&rdquo; The model decides <em>when</em> to call a tool; your client runs the call and feeds the result back.
    Connect three servers and the model can suddenly read your code, query your database, and search the web, all in one
    conversation.
  </p>

  <h2>The categories worth knowing</h2>
  <p>
    The community directory, <a href="https://github.com/punkpeye/awesome-mcp-servers">awesome-mcp-servers</a>,
    catalogues thousands of servers across roughly 45 categories. A handful cover most real-world use:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>File systems</strong> (<code>filesystem</code>): read, write, and move local files. The first server most people connect.</li>
    <li><strong>Version control and dev tools</strong> (<code>git</code>, <code>github</code>): branches and commits locally; issues and pull requests on GitHub.</li>
    <li><strong>Databases</strong> (<code>postgres</code>, <code>sqlite</code>): run real queries, read-only or read-write, against your data.</li>
    <li><strong>Browser automation</strong> (<code>playwright</code>, <code>puppeteer</code>): drive a real browser to click, fill forms, and scrape pages.</li>
    <li><strong>Search and fetch</strong> (<code>brave-search</code>, <code>fetch</code>): search the live web and read pages, which gets the model past its <a class="kb-term" href="/dictionary/training-cutoff">training cutoff</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Communication</strong> (<code>slack</code>): read and post messages, manage channels.</li>
    <li><strong>Knowledge and memory</strong> (<code>memory</code>): a store the model can write to and recall across sessions, a simple form of <a class="kb-term" href="/dictionary/agent">agent</a> memory.</li>
    <li><strong>Cloud and monitoring</strong>: connect to AWS, GCP, Sentry, and similar, so the model can read logs and resources.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to read the list</h2>
  <p>
    Each entry on awesome-mcp-servers is tagged so you can pick well. The emoji legend marks the <strong>language</strong>
    it is written in (Python, TypeScript, Go, Rust, and others), the <strong>scope</strong>, a local service that runs on
    your machine or a cloud service that runs remotely, and the supported <strong>operating systems</strong>. The
    local-versus-cloud mark is the one to read first, and not only for convenience.
  </p>

  <div class="mts" id="mts">
    <div class="mts-head">Hands-on: match the task to the server</div>
    <p class="mts-q" id="mts-q"></p>
    <div class="mts-opts" id="mts-opts"></div>
    <p class="mts-reveal" id="mts-reveal" hidden></p>
    <div class="mts-foot"><span id="mts-prog"></span><button id="mts-next" type="button" hidden>Next &rarr;</button></div>
  </div>

  <h2>Local versus cloud, and the trust line</h2>
  <p>
    A local server runs on your computer and can touch your real files, environment variables, and credentials. That is
    exactly what makes it useful, and exactly why you should only run servers you trust and have looked at. Treat adding
    an MCP server like installing a browser extension with full access: convenient, powerful, and worth a moment of
    caution. Cloud servers move that trust to a third party instead. The <a href="/what-is-mcp#security">security note in
    the MCP explainer</a> goes deeper.
  </p>

  <h2>Connecting one</h2>
  <p>
    Connecting a server is usually a small block of JSON in your client&rsquo;s config file (for Claude Desktop, that is
    <code>claude_desktop_config.json</code>): the command to start the server, its arguments, and any keys it needs.
    Build a valid one, or paste an existing block to validate it, with the
    <a href="/mcp-config-generator">MCP Config Generator</a>. Restart the client, and the server&rsquo;s tools show up
    ready for the model to call.
  </p>

  <h2>Where to go next</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/what-is-mcp">What is MCP</a>, the protocol underneath all of this.</li>
    <li><a href="/mcp-config-generator">MCP Config Generator</a>, build the config to connect a server.</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/punkpeye/awesome-mcp-servers">awesome-mcp-servers</a>, the curated directory to browse thousands more.</li>
  </ul>
</AiPage>

<style is:global>
  .mts{border:1.5px solid var(--line);border-radius:14px;background:var(--cream);padding:16px 18px;margin:24px 0}
  .mts-head{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--coral)}
  .mts-q{font-size:15.5px;color:var(--ink);font-weight:600;margin:10px 0 12px}
  .mts-opts{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:8px}
  .mts-opts button{border:1.5px solid var(--line);background:var(--paper);border-radius:10px;padding:8px 13px;font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:12.5px;color:var(--ink);cursor:pointer;transition:border-color .12s,background .12s}
  .mts-opts button:hover{border-color:var(--coral)}
  .mts-opts button:disabled{cursor:default}
  .mts-opts button.right{border-color:#0f9f82;background:rgba(15,159,130,.12)}
  .mts-opts button.wrong{border-color:var(--coral);background:rgba(238,75,43,.08)}
  .mts-reveal{margin:12px 0 0;font-size:14px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--ink);background:var(--paper-2);border-radius:10px;padding:11px 13px}
  .mts-reveal code{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:.92em;background:rgba(30,24,19,.08);padding:1px 5px;border-radius:5px}
  .mts-foot{display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;margin-top:12px;min-height:30px}
  .mts-foot span{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:12px;color:var(--ink-soft)}
  #mts-next{border:0;background:var(--coral);color:#fff;font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:13px;padding:7px 15px;border-radius:9px;cursor:pointer}
</style>

<script is:inline>
  (function () {
    var Q = [
      { task: "Let the AI read, write, and reorganize files in a project folder.", opts: ["filesystem", "postgres", "brave-search", "slack"], a: 0, why: "A <code>filesystem</code> server exposes read, write, and list-directory tools over a folder you allow. It is the File Systems category, and usually the first server people connect." },
      { task: "Let the AI run SQL queries against your app's Postgres database.", opts: ["github", "postgres", "puppeteer", "memory"], a: 1, why: "A <code>postgres</code> server (Databases) gives the model a run-query tool against a real database. You choose whether it is read-only or read-write." },
      { task: "Let the AI search the live web and read the pages it finds.", opts: ["sqlite", "filesystem", "brave-search", "git"], a: 2, why: "<code>brave-search</code> (Search and fetch) returns live results, getting the model past its training cutoff. Pair it with a <code>fetch</code> server to read the pages." },
      { task: "Let the AI open issues and read pull requests in your repo.", opts: ["github", "slack", "filesystem", "postgres"], a: 0, why: "The <code>github</code> server (Version control and dev tools) exposes issues, pull requests, and repository contents. <code>git</code> is its local-only cousin for commits and branches." },
      { task: "Let the AI click through a real website and fill in a form.", opts: ["brave-search", "playwright", "memory", "postgres"], a: 1, why: "<code>playwright</code> (or <code>puppeteer</code>) drives a real browser, so the model can click, type, and scrape. That is the Browser Automation category." }
    ];
    var i = 0, answered = false;
    var qEl = document.getElementById('mts-q'), optsEl = document.getElementById('mts-opts'),
        rev = document.getElementById('mts-reveal'), prog = document.getElementById('mts-prog'), next = document.getElementById('mts-next');
    function show() {
      answered = false;
      var q = Q[i];
      qEl.textContent = q.task;
      optsEl.innerHTML = '';
      q.opts.forEach(function (o, k) {
        var b = document.createElement('button'); b.type = 'button'; b.textContent = o; b.dataset.k = k;
        optsEl.appendChild(b);
      });
      rev.hidden = true; next.hidden = true;
      prog.textContent = 'Question ' + (i + 1) + ' of ' + Q.length;
    }
    optsEl.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
      var b = e.target.closest('button'); if (!b || answered) return;
      answered = true;
      var q = Q[i], k = +b.dataset.k, ok = k === q.a;
      Array.prototype.forEach.call(optsEl.children, function (c) {
        c.disabled = true;
        if (+c.dataset.k === q.a) c.classList.add('right');
        else if (c === b) c.classList.add('wrong');
      });
      rev.innerHTML = (ok ? '<strong>Correct.</strong> ' : '<strong>The right pick is ' + q.opts[q.a] + '.</strong> ') + q.why;
      rev.hidden = false;
      next.hidden = (i >= Q.length - 1);
      if (i >= Q.length - 1) prog.textContent = 'Done, you have seen all ' + Q.length + '.';
    });
    next.addEventListener('click', function () { if (i < Q.length - 1) { i++; show(); } });
    show();
  })();
</script>
